HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: Pleasant 78-year-old female with history of lung cancer with remote partial pneumonectomy, some element of COPD and chronic respiratory failure on home oxygen therapy. She presents with worsening shortness of breath, which started rather abruptly the day prior to presentation. On arrival to the ED she was mildly tachypneic and slightly tachycardic and appeared to be in mild respiratory distress. Her O2 had been titrated to 4 L/m nasal cannula in order to sustain SaO2 values in the 90% or above range. Patient also noted to have pallor. No hematemesis, melena, hematochezia, abdominal pain, fever, cough or known exposure to COVID. Patient reports having received her first COVID vaccination just over one 1 week ago. A hypochromic microcytic anemia, progressive, was noted with a hemoglobin of 7.4 g/dL. Patient reported that she was up-to-date on EGD and colonoscopy within the past year without findings of acute pathology or bleeding. A CTA of the chest was conducted with findings of bilateral pulmonary emboli. She denies lower extremity swelling, pain or tenderness. Patient placed in observation in order to provide palliative blood replacement therapy and commence with anticoagulation for venous thromboembolism.  DISCHARGE SUMMARY/OBSERVATION COURSE: Uneventful observation course for this pleasant 78-year-old female who presented with somewhat sudden worsening of her chronic shortness of breath and was found to have CTA evidence of bilateral pulmonary emboli. This in the setting of a progressive iron deficiency anemia without evidence of active clinical gastrointestinal bleeding. The patient received 2 units of packed red blood cells in a palliative fashion for her presenting hemoglobin of 7.4 g/dL. Posttransfusion hemoglobin was 10.1 g/dL. Concurrently, she was placed on weight-based low molecular weight heparin for full anticoagulation. I examined the patient on the morning of February 12 and found her to be nondistressed. Her SaO2 value was 96% on 4 L/m nasal cannula O2. Recall that her baseline flow rate historically had been 2 L/m his cannula. Etiology of the patient's thromboembolism uncertain. She had no clinical findings of unilateral or bilateral lower extremity swelling or tenderness. Patient noted to be a survivor of both breast and lung cancers but without known evidence of active persistent malignancy. Of interest, she had received a COVID-19 vaccine just over one week prior to presentation. I contacted pharmacy in this regard and encouraged him to report possible adverse event via VAERS. I recommended a course of rivaroxaban and provided a prescription with a VTE dosing schedule. Patient was advised to followup with Dr in 10 days.  M.D., Hospital Medicine    MD Feb 12, 2021 08:40

Then on Sunday, the pain was even worse and I could still not touch any teeth together and my bite was so off that my lower teeth did protrude out beyond my upper teeth. I went to the doctor the next day (Monday) in which he gave me a prescription for Meloxicam to reduce the inflammation. I had taken ibuprofen the days prior with no effect at all. Meloxicam did not work that much better but did reduce the inflammation a little bit. Patient began feeling ill within 24 hours of getting second COVID19 vaccination. Presented to our hospital the evening of 1/28/21 with generalized weakness, fevers, near syncope. Extensive workup revealed likely hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis syndrome attributed to reaction to vaccine. Patient treated with blood transfusions, corticosteroid (dexamethasone 20mg) and folic acid 1mg daily. Patient also developed rectus sheath hematoma attributed to vaccine/reaction. Patient continues to remain hospitalized 15 days later. Clinically stable, yet critically ill with no significant / some worsening of laboratory results.
LAB_DATA: On admission, fever of 101.3, WBC 2.6, HgB 8.2, PLT 77k. Nadir (2/11) WBC 0.7, HgB 6.0, PLT 42k. Bone marrow biopsy collected 2/5 demonstrated "rare hemophagocytic histiocytes." On 2/4, ferritin was 6115. On 2/9/21, IL-2 receptor alpha was 1023. Constellation of fever, bycytopenia, elevated ferritin and IL-2 all consistent with HLH. Notably, triglycerides and fibrinogen were normal / inconsistent with HLH. CT on 1/29/21 demonstrated possible enterocolitis. Repeat CT on 2/1 showed rectus sheath hematoma.

After I received the shot, I went to the waiting area.  While sitting down, I started to feel chest pain.  Then, I felt dizzy.  The dizziness lasted a very short period of time.  Nevertheless, the chest pain lasted for about 30 to 40 minutes.  The pain did decrease over that period of time to the point where it just felt like heartburn.  About 20 to 30 minutes and while still having a little chest pain, I began to feel a tingling sensation with pain on my right hand.  The tingling sensation did not last long, but the pain lasted for about 15 minutes.  I did share my symptoms closer to 30 minutes after experiencing them because I thought they were typical side effects.  After I got home, I still felt heartburn and pain in my left arm where I received the shot.  At around 8 p.m., I remembered that I still had the bandaid that was put on my arm.  I took it off in the dark.  But, I decided to turn on the light because my arm still hurt.  This is when I saw a huge, red, oval-shaped rash on the area where I got the shot.  Again, it hurt but did not itch.  The next day (today), I called my doctor.  He said I got a local reaction and it would be okay as long as it did not increase.  To my knowledge, it did not increase.  I did take pictures of my rash today.  I did not take any additional action since this is the only side effect that has remained.  And, my doctor said that I would be okay.
ALLERGIES: While not medically diagnosed, I have had negative reactions to coffee and perfumed products, including facial products.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: "Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine "  pt received vaccine to his left arm. 10 min later (1335) he reported feeling dizzy. allergy tech and i evaluated pt. pt clammy with sweat noted to the back of his neck. pt speaking in full complete sentences. no increased WOB. left radial pulse regular and not elevated, not thready. no hives found. denied itchiness. asked pt if he felt anything stuck in his throat, he swallowed a few times and said "yes". asked if he had much water today, he said no. pt reported it felt a little hard to breathe in his throat. i had him remove his mask. pt reported nausea. denied abdominal pain. had him take a few sips of water. reported he no longer felt anything stuck in his throat, no longer hard to breathe in his throat. pt reported tingling in his left arm. pt worked the night shift. went to work at 1600 on 2/11. ate at 2000, beef and potatoes. had snacks. ate chicken and rice at 0300. usually has a full gallon of water on shift but only had a half gallon. got off at 0400. went to sleep at 0530. usually wakes at 1445-1500 but woke up earlier for this appt. appt was at 1330 but he was here early. had a protein shake 30 min before arrival but has not had much water. thinking the protein shake was causing his symptoms. denies working out today, denied energy drink intake, denied any coffee. pt took a large amount of water and then threw up. pt reported he felt much better. nausea resolved. still no itchiness. no hives. no clamminess. no trouble breathing. no globus. no dizziness. no tingling in his left arm. resolved by 1340. held Epi given he reported complete resolution of his symptoms. seemed likely the combination of being underhydrated, having slept less than usual, facility being a little warm and him wearing a mask and possibly his protein shake contributed. had patient wait 30 minutes (1410). allergy tech sat with patient who continued to speak in full sentences, tell stories, etc. had him stand up slowly. denied dizziness. still no hives, no itchiness, no globus, no trouble breathing, no nausea, no abdominal pain. advised pt of reasons to call 911 (he lives on base where we have ambulance services). advised i would be placing a VAERS report.
OTHER_MEDS: denied energy drinks, coffee. did not ask about OTC meds  or dietary supplements or herbal remedies.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came in and got her first dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine at 1515. Patient stated she had no allergies and no issues with vaccines in the past. Patient received the vaccine in the right deltoid, IM. Patient tolerated procedure well. Patient walked to main lobby to wait for her 15 min observation time by a staff member. Approximately 5 minutes after receiving the vaccine the patient approached the staff member observing patients that are in their observation window and stated ?something doesn?t feel right?. At this time the staff member called for a nurse to the lobby. When I got to the lobby and asked the patient what was going on she stated ?that she feels weird in her entire body?. I asked the patient if she was able to walk and took her back to the clinic to an exam room. Once in the exam room the patient stated that she ?just feels weird and that her heart is racing?. The patient started to get red blotchy spots on her shoulders. The patient stated that she was having no trouble breathing and did not feel like her throat or tongue was swelling. The patient?s blood pressure was 190/100, HR 89 and oxygen saturation was 98%. I gave the patient 50 mg of Benadryl PO. Patient stated she was only allergic to erythromycin and takes sertraline and vitamins as her only medications. I had the patient lay down as she felt a little dizzy. The patient was breathing heavily but was not having any trouble with SOB at this time, she called her husband to come join her. The patient continued to feel the same symptoms but they were not worsening. Approximately 5 minutes later her blood pressure had decreased to 170/94. The patient stated that she was feeling the same. 20 minutes after the patient took the Benadryl her red blotchy spots had decreased and she was starting ?to feel better overall?. The patients husband stated that he would watch her tonight and continue to monitor for symptoms. I recommended that she go in and be evaluated if her symptoms persist. The patients blood pressure 30 minutes after taking Benadryl was 140/94, pulse 73, oxygen 97%. The patient left with her husband with the understanding that if her symptoms get worse or persist to go in and be seen.

At 4:55, patient received a COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine. At the time of administration patient expressed she had experienced a previous reaction to a pneumonia vaccination (unknown time frame) and that she did not like to receive shots. She requested that the person administering the vaccine count down before giving shot. Patient appeared nervous and was breathing heavily before she received her vaccine. Patient was instructed to sit and wait 15 mins. after vaccine administration in case of an adverse reaction. At time of check-out from the pharmacy (15 mins. after vaccination), patient expressed to pharmacy intern that she felt a "little dizzy" and that she had experienced "slurred speech" immediately after having received the vaccine, however had not communicated this to pharmacy staff. Pharmacy intern immediately took patients blood pressure and it was 176/99 mmHg and 162/101 mmHg during first two blood pressure checks. The pharmacy staff requested patient to remain within the pharmacy premises so that she could be monitored for more time. She then was checked every 5-10 minutes for approximately 2 hours. During this time, she described vision changes, dizziness, and a strange "fogginess" around her head. Additional blood pressure monitoring was conducted for results of 158/100 mmHg and 195/100 mmHg. Pharmacy Manager discussed options with patient, including having her go to an Urgent Care facility or calling 911, so that paramedics could assess her. patient expressed she wanted to be taken to the hospital, therefore intern called 911. Paramedics arrived shortly after and determined patient had not experienced a stroke. Her neurological exam was negative. Paramedics stated that patient was most likely experiencing an allergic reaction. The paramedics then proceeded to take patient to the hospital at her request around 7:00 PM. Multiple pharmacists and pharmacy interns spoke with her during this time frame of ~2-2.5 hours, took her blood pressure, and assessed her condition.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient expressed she had her arm swell ("got really big") with a pneumonia shot. Unknown date and unknown vaccination.
ALLERGIES: Unknown - however patient reports having a reaction after a pneumonia shot once. Patient stated her arm "got really big."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient called staff over and told him she was going to faint. staff got senior nurse to help assess. Other nurse which was at pt site. Patient leaning forward and then sat back head tilted backwards, eyes opened and non-responsive. Sternal rub performed and other noxious stimuli performed. Continued until pt became responsive. app less than a minute late patient became responsive. Alert and Oriented X 4, Vital signs obtained. encouraged Patient to drink water and take deep breaths. Patient stated incident of fainting occurred prior in dermatologist office. No follow-up care was given after the doctors visit. patient became nauseas and vomited. She was clamy and pale. Patient was encouraged to go to the hospital and would not let us call EMS. Said she would not take public trasportation home. She will take a cab and call her PCP  in the morning and follow-up care. Staff verbalized that it was unsafe for her to go home rather than the hospital. patient denied any further dizziness, nausea or respiratory distress. Stated she  just felt unwell and needed to rest . Staff made her sign "Refusal of Immediate Care Against Medical Advice". Patient then called uber and staffed member escorted pt into cab at 7.12pm. We attempted to call patient multiple times between 7.23 pm - 7.30 pm.
ALLERGIES: Cats and it makes her sneeze.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt attended a drive through vaccination clinic. About 15 minutes after the vaccine was given the pt notified staff that her tongue was swelling.  The medical provider went to her vehicle, pt was found alert and in no acute distress. Pts tongue was edematous with about a 30% increase in size beyond baseline.  Pt was given a single dose of epinephrine 0.3mg IM in her right thigh. Pt was escorted into the clinic. BP 166/98 HR 86 RR18 SpO2 99%RA. Pt was given Solumedrol 60mg IM and diphenhydramine 50mg PO.  Pt complained of itchy skin. No skin rashes visible.  Pt was monitored. Tongue swelling resolved, no other complaints.  At 1630 VSS and PE was normal Pt was discharged home by personal vehicle driven by patients friend. Pt given  strict ER precautions.

She has not had any symptoms since then.

I received the Pfizer vaccine through my employer,  and shortly after I had an abrupt loss of taste and smell (with no other symptoms). The first round I received was on 12/21/20 (#EK5730), followed by another on 1/11/21 (#EL1284).  That Sunday, 1/17/21, I suddenly noticed I lost my sense of taste while eating dinner. I didn't notice the loss of smell right away, but did notice it later in the evening.  To my knowledge, I have never had covid. I immediately requested to get tested for covid that Monday, on 1/18/21 - 2 days later, the results came back negative. Because I've heard of false negatives being common, I requested to get another test, which my employer authorized a week later, on 1/25/21. The test came back negative for covid again, after 2-3 days. As a last ditch effort, I went to the urgent care on Tuesday, 2/2/21, to get some bloodwork done and some reassurance. Patient with COPD here to receive her 1st dose of Moderna COVID vaccine.  Patient was feeling well prior and her husband states she has not had any breathing issues for 2 months. Approximately 10 minutes after receiving her immunization, she developed a dry, tight cough but lung sounds were initially clear.  Over the next 10 minutes she progressed to audible wheezing.  She took 3 puffs of her home albuterol inhaler.  Oxygen saturation was 99% but patient reported no improvement with her inhaler.  Acute bronchospasm secondary to vaccine administration  Patient was given albuterol 2.5 mg via nebulizer along with 25 mg Benadryl.  Following the nebulizer treatment, lung sounds were  once again clear, audible wheezing was gone, and patient was feeling back to baseline.  She  was given 125 mg Solumedrol to prevent relapse of symptoms.  Advised use of nebulizer  every 4 hours as needed today if cough or wheezing returns.  As for her second dose, we discussed pretreating with Benadryl 25 mg and an albuterol nebulizer treatment prior to  arriving. I would recommend she be monitored for 30 minutes when she receives it as well and be ready with Solumedrol and Epinephrine in the event she has issues.  Husband and patient encouraged to call back if worsening issues today.
OTHER_MEDS: PROVENTIL; albuterol inhaler; FOSAMAX; aspirin; LIPITOR; FLONASE; fluticasone-umeclidin-vilant; GLUCOTROL XL; BAYER CONTOUR NEXT TEST; HYDRODIURIL; DUONEB; Jardiance; CLARITIN; Melatonin; MOBIC; NAMENDA XR; GLUCOPHAGE; LOPRESSOR; DULERA; SI

2/10/21 -  I am writing to report that yesterday, at 10:00 AM, I received my first Pfizer Covid19 vaccination.  Prior to receiving my vaccination I reported that while I have had no adverse reactions after receiving flu, shingles, or other previous vaccinations, in the past, I have had strong allergic reactions after consuming mollusks or foods that have come in contact with mollusks.  I was advised that I would be required to wait on site for 30 minutes after my Pfizer vaccination so that I could be monitored for any adverse reaction from it.  After waiting 30 minutes, my husband and I were cleared to go home.    At 2:30 PM, I started to experience a swelling of my tongue and throat.  I immediately took three 25 mg Benadryl tablets as I have done when I experienced past allergic reactions.  I also began to consume significant amounts of water to help with swallowing.  I then called my husband and asked him to come home.    At about 3:30 PM, the swelling of my tongue began to diminish and by 4:30 PM I began to swallow more easily and was able to reduce consumption of water.     I had a very light dinner at 5:30 PM, and went to bed at 8:30 PM.  At 10:00 PM I went to sleep.  I slept somewhat restlessly and woke at 5:00 AM as I usually do.     Today, though tired, I'm okay.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a mild reaction of rash after my first vaccine 1/14/21 but it went way after taking 25mgs of Benadryl. The second shot I was instructed to pre medicate with Benadryl before hand. After my second shot 2/11/21, within about 5-10 minutes I started with a red hot spot on my left ear, and a rash at injection site. Then it spread down my arm and to my chest. I took another 25 mgs of Benadryl and was given Pepcid as well. My chest started getting a tightness feeling in it and then I was instructed to go to the Emergency Room. I was gocen solu-medrol in IV and it seemed to help.  The next morning 2/12/21 I took 25 mgs of Benadryl prophylactically. At 1142, I started feeling like the rash was coming back. It started under my chin and spread all over my face to my neck and chest and to my arms. My chest started feeling tight again. My blood pressure was 154/94, pulse 108. I got in touch with the nurse who was with me the night before with my first reaction and she instructed me to go to the ER again. There they gave me another round of solu-medrol IV. And sent me home with steroids to take.  Today, 2/13/21 I woke up and my face still is rashy and hot to the touch, my eyes are puffy and tongue is more swollen than usual and my chest still feels tight. The day of the shot, I was fine.   But I went to bed at about 10:00 that night and slept very little.  I was chilling so badly that I couldn't get to sleep!  When I got out of bed in the morning, I could barely move due to severe muscle pain.  I did very little all day, suffering from what felt like the flu:  chills, loss of appetite, and "brain fog" such that I couldn't read or think clearly.  My head felt warm, but I never took my temperature.  The next morning, I noticed hives on my chest between my breasts and around the armpit of my left arm.   The following morning, now  about 45 hours after my second injection, I still had pink hives, and my left armpit was swollen so that it wasn't concave, as it always is, but convex.  Touching my armpit hurt, and I think some gland in it was swollen.   Similarly,  a gland on the left side of my neck was swollen and painful to the touch.  Today, now  the fourth day since the injection, the hives have subsided, and my glands are almost back to normal.  Overall, I am very glad to have had the opportunity to get the vaccine, but I haven't felt that sick in years.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the shot at 9 am on 2/9/2021.  On 2/10/2021, I had a slight headache and had body aches. I took ibuprofen and laid down for a short while and it subsided before bed on 2/10/2021.   I woke up at 12am on 2/11/2021 with bilateral hands numbness and tingling in bilateral feet.  Within a few minutes of walking around, the numbness subsided and became very strong pins and needles in my hands.  Around 3 am, the pins and needles intensity had decreased but tingling had come up from fingertips to armpits and from toes to mid thigh but the intensity of the paresthesia was decreasing.  Around 8 am, I noticed that my coordination (could be weakness, I couldn't determine what it was) in my upper extremities was off when I was unloading the dishwasher.  I was able to unload without dropping anything but I was definitely off.  I called employee health when they opened (I was given the shot at the hospital where I work) and they said to call PCP immediately.  I called an MD office who said I needed to go to the ER but I could feel it improving so I didn't want to go to the ER.  Around 10am on 2/11/2021, the temperature sensation in my arms was off.  One felt very hot and the other was cold sensation and freezing to the touch and the bottom of my feet felt like I was standing on ice.  I ended up calling MDlive because I did feel like it was getting better and didn't want to go to the ER.  Telehealth MD said to go to the ER to rule out Guillian Barre.  I called another doc who said they would see me.  I went to new PCP at 1330.  At this time, I tingling was in the bottom of my feet and some in the hands and sporadically throughout the arms and legs but again with less intensity.  MD ran bloodwork to rule out another cause.  Bloodwork came back normal so they said that they after talking with MD, NP and MD thought the that this is a reaction to vaccine and I had no progressing weakness so they ruled out Gullian Barre but instructed me to go to ER if worsened.  The paresthia was only in my big toe and fingers in left hand when I went to bed on 2/12/2021.  I did wake up around 0300 on 2/13/2021 with  numbness in my left pinky finger and half of my ring finger was eventually subsided. I have had sporadic tingling sensation in my feet and in my hands today but with very little intensity.
LAB_DATA: 1)CBC with Diff - Normal results except the following: (however MD was not concerned since they were very close to the normal range) Mean Corpuscular HGB Conc 32.1 Mean Platelet Volume 10.7 Lymph % 22.3 2)Vitamin B12 - Normal 3) Vitamin D - Normal 4) Free T4 Thyroxine - Normal 5) TSH - Normal 3)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No reaction noticed immediatly.  Noticed sore left upper arm on 2.7 and some chills that day.  Arm continued to ache in area of shot and became red and swollen over time.  Then on Wed. 2/10 it became large area as big as my hand, swollen pillow but hard, red, hot, and itchy.  Toward 11 p.m.  my nasal passage and lips began to swell and I began to take benedryl to control the allergic reaction.  I took 25 mg tablets (2), then 45 min later 1 more, then 45 min later 1 more until the problem was not getting worse.  In morning problem was still at that level so I took another benedryl and called doctor.  They set up appointment for me  and I saw Dr.   on 2.12.21. He suspected that it was a delayed reaction to the vaccination and prescribed prednosol.  Suggested that I do not take the 2nd part of vaccination series due to this reaction.  He did find some confirmation of rare but similar reactions on line.  Took a picture for his files and referred me to this site.

Called to see patient ~10 min after prime dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccination. Patient reported acute onset of left eye swelling sensation and throat tightening. Was able to talk without difficulty. Normal salivation.    Moved immediately from observation area to treatment room. Reaffirmed that symptoms persisted and that time she also reported chest tightness. Vitals were normal and pulse oximetry = 99%. Exam conducted while vitals being measured. No wheeze or stridor. No rash. No obvious oral lesions or swelling. Eye lids not swollen. Epi IM given at once (within 1-2 min of arrival at the treatment room).    Symptoms resolved over the next 10 mins. Vitals were monitored frequently. Heart rate was increased before and just after Epi then dropped to ~70 b/m. Other vitals also remained normal and she was comfortable.   EMS was called and she was transported to ED for continued observation. Husband accompanied her.  She was seen in ED and observed for 4 hours. Benadryl, Pepcid and Prednisone taper prescribed. She was released from ED.

LAB_DATA: Routine screening mammogram done on 11-13-2020.  3 suspicious lesions were further investigated with additional mammogram views and a left breast ultrasound with attention to the upper outer quadrant of left breast on 11-19-2020.  Two lesions in the right breast were deemed stable when compared to prior mammograms dating back 5 years.  The lesion in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast was deemed likely benign and I was offered biopsy vs. increased monitoring with imaging q 6 months.  I chose the latter.  With those baseline studies available, on 12-30-2020, I had another ultrasound of the left breast focused on the region of mastitis in the lower outer quadrant which did not show any suspicious lesions.  I was seen by my PCP on 1-7-2021 who referred to a breast surgeon for further follow up and a decision about how to follow this after I had healed from the acute infection.  I saw breast surgical oncology clinic on 1-19-2021.  He did a repeat ultrasound of the left breast focused on the prior region of mastitis, the lower outer quadrant.  He saw no suspicious areas and his impression was that I had average risk for breast cancer overall.  He recommended the next diagnostic breast ultrasound be done on 5-18-2021 and bilateral breast screening mammography due on 11-19-2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: minor fever and sore arm until bedtime. I awoke about 10:30 PM with nausea and abdominal pain, even to the touch, higher fever, mild headache and significant thirst. When I awoke a few hours later and tried to get out of bed my feet were cramping so I couldn't stand comfortably, also achiness in ankles, hands and wrists. I was very thirsty and cold, so cold that I could not get a thermometer in my mouth as my teeth  were chattering. I tried to drink some water and went back to bed. A few hours later I woke up, thirsty, kind of crawled into the bathroom. I had a 101 temperature, still nauseous and achy joints. I tossed and turned all night. When I got up at 6:15 AM I went into the bathroom, tried to drink water but was feeling very nauseous and felt like I was going to pass out. I woke up on the floor when my husband came in - he heard my head hit the floor from another room. My first instinct was  for water, which he squirted into my mouth. Both of my arms and hand were tingling. He managed to help me up, and I crawled back to the bed. My temp was about 100.5 where it stayed for most of the day. I called a friend, she told me to take some ibuprofen -I can't take acetaminophen- I took one, drank lots of fluids, and spent the rest of the day sleeping on and off. I did cut my head but not significantly enough to go to a facility.  I was literally unable to do anything for the entire day. When I woke up today my temperature was down to 98.1 - its normally in the 97's - and feel much better except my sore arm and aching head
PRIOR_VAX: very swollen arm with pertussis vaccine about 40 years ago

After Covid vaccination #1, patient was instructed to be monitored for 30 minutes due to history of sulfa allergy.  After about 5 minutes of observation, she approached me (pharmacist) saying she had tingling and a little numbness in right side of lower face.  She reported no difficulty breathing and no other symptoms.  I consulted the two other pharmacists I was with and we decided to not take any immediate action but continue monitoring.  I checked in with patient every few minutes to ask if symptoms were getting better/worse.  For first 30 minutes, pt said symptoms were the same.  After about 30 minutes, she said she had a little itching down her throat, but still no difficulty breathing.  We gave her 50 mg diphenhydramine and monitored for 30 more minutes.  After 1 full hour of observation, she never reported difficulty breathing.  She did get tired from the Benadryl and was up on moving around and said feeling slightly better.  After 1 hour, she went back to her room.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received vaccine at 1:48pm at PODsite. Initially, no reaction. By following morning, 2/11, woke with sore arm, slightly stiff neck, and heart palpitations that persisted throughout the day. Had trouble sleeping as palpitations continued throughout the night and varied in degree from a flutter to a thump. No chest pain, no chest pressure and no breathing issues. By morning of 2/12, symptoms were still present and numbness in both arms from elbow to finger tips occurred. Called my healthcare nurse's line for advice to determine if I should see my doctor or go to ER. I was advised to visit the ER. Arrived at ER at approximately 12:56pm where I was immediately admitted and assigned to doctor. After my first 30-60 mins of observation, I was informed that my heart rate and blood pressure were high. I informed doctor that I have never had high blood pressure, so that is unusual. Was discharged around 4pm and instructed to submit an adverse reaction report and to see my general practitioner in 2 days. I was informed the following: no evidence of an acute cardiopulmonary process.  Heart size and contours are normal.
LAB_DATA: The doctor and team of nurses checked my vitals, asked why I was there and quickly ran a variety of tests including: EKG, X-ray, blood work, urine sample, all while I was attached to a heart rate and blood pressure monitor. I was given IV fluids, magnesium, and metoprolol (5 mg).
HISTORY: Limb girdle muscular dystrophy Brain aneurysm

Patient had ongoing pain, eventually returned to primary provider.  The provider denied vaccination could cause the symptoms, prescribed tramadol and meloxicam, ordered xray and physical therapy. SYMPTOM_TEXT: While administering the vaccine I was sitting on a stool with wheels.  The bolt had at some point become loosened and when I shifted my weight forward on the stool to administer the vaccination  the wheel came off and the stool came out from underneath me.  I had administered the vaccination but had not pulled the syringe from the patients arm when this happened.  I  landed on the floor looking up at the patient.  The  vaccine had been administered but the syringe was still in the patients arm.  I immediately jumped up and removed the syringe.  The syringe came out smoothly.  The needle was not bent.  I immediately placed the syringe in the sharps container per vaccination protocol.  The  patient did bleed.   Though no more than  with previous patients who have a superficial capillary nick.   The patient did not move during the incident.  He did not  move his arm or rise or jump.  He was surprised and stayed immobile.   I immediately asked if he was ok and he stated he has never bled before from a vaccination.  The patient stayed the requisite 20 minutes post vaccination waiting period.   Before the patient left I removed the band aid to inspect the vaccination site.  The area was red, but did not seem to have a tear or wound.  The patient stated he felt fine.
ALLERGIES: no severe allergies listed per vaccine informed consent

I noticed no change in my swelling and my throat started to feel like there was a lump. At around 10:20 am,  I drove to the emergency room. The doctor noticed swelling in my lips and some in my tongue and throat. I was given cimetidine and methylprednisolone through an IV, which reduced the swelling. I was discharged 2 hours later after the swelling went down and was given 2 prescriptions to take the next 4 days, which were prednisone 20mg  (three tablets once a day) and famotidine 20mg (twice a day). There is some swelling in my lips in the morning (for the last two days) until I take the steroids, then it reduces the swelling. The overall cost of the emergency room visit was $1669.17.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Delayed reaction to the vaccine that began 6 days after first dose and persisted for approximately 3 days. I first became itchy on my abdomen and arms, I then developed flat oval hives and my eyes and upper lip began swelling. My throat did not swell. I took 2 Benadryl that evening that helped the itch and caused the facial swelling to subside somewhat. I slept thru the night and when the Benadryl wore off in the morning, the same symptoms returned. I took 1 Benadryl which again calmed the symptoms. The same symptoms returned in the evening and I went to an Urgent Care. I was prescribed Prednisone and more Benadryl. These medicines helped to calm the symptoms even more, but the itchiness and hives did come and go thru the next day. On day 3 I took Zyrtec in addition to my last dose of Predisone and the itchiness subsided completely. I took one more dose of Zyrtec the next day and the symptoms have not returned. I followed up with my PCM who tested for a Hazelnut allergy as I had eaten them that first night. She also referred me to an Allergist. I saw the Allergist who said in their opinion my immune system was having a reaction to the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine and classified me as "medium risk" for the second dose. He recommended that I still get the second dose and to premeditate with Zyrtec the night before, day of and for 7 days following.
LAB_DATA: Hazelnut allergy Feb 8. Still awaiting results.

Cellulitic Sweet's syndrome of lower extremity. Significant LLE erythema and pain out of proportion to exam that has continued to progress despite broad-spectrum antibiotics, now s/p OR cut down x3 with no e/o necrotizing fasciitis. Initially most c/f infection/cellulitis, however in discussion with ID, rheum, and derm and given progression of rash in s/o broad spectrum Abx and negative tissue cultures, now most suspicious for cellulitic variant of Sweet's syndrome (SS). Pathology report w/neutrohpliic inflammation w/evidence of ischemia, w/o evidence of infection, c/w Sweets Syndrome. While this is a rare disorder, it primarily occurs in the setting of recent infection or malignancy. Currently working up potentially triggers. Infectious work up thus far negative. Hematologic malignancy most often linked with SS, given new and worsening pancytopenia, will consult heme for recommendations for additional work up. Other potential triggers include vaccinations (question about COVID vaccine recently) and often idiopathic. Maintain of treatment for SS is steroids, dermatology currently managing dosing.

I also felt very faint when standing and thought I may pass out.  3 times when standing, I had to quickly sit down to avoid it. I do suffer from vasovagal syncope so this may be unrelated to vaccination. I took Tylenol and drank more water. Temp rose to about 100.6 before beginning to drop at around 4 am. I continued to take Tylenol every 4 hours and it helped keep temp below 100 but towards the end of the 4 hours, it would start to rise again. I ate normally and drank extra water due to feeling dehydrated still. Around 1 PM 2/12 I started to feel nauseous and had an upset stomach. I was still have a general body aches and elevated temperature around 99.5. My normal temp is usually about 98.0. Nausea led to diarrhea 1 time. Symptoms continued until approximately 8 pm when very quickly the body aches, nausea, fever and soreness in injection arm all went away. None of these symptoms have returned and it is now 2/13 at 8 pm.   I did test positive for Covid-19 on December 28, 2020 but have been fully recovered with no symptoms since 1/8/2021.

syncope, c/o itchy throat Narrative: Patient was seen prior to administration of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccination. He has allergies to bees/egg and a h/o anaphylaxis 2/2 receiving an injection of penicillin in the past. Discussed that prior h/o anaphylaxis to PCN injection was not a contraindication to this vaccination, but is a precaution. Discussed risks of receiving the vaccination vs benefits of the vaccine, which patient states "I already had this discussion with Dr.!" He has multiple comorbidities which place him at a higher risk for more severe illness from COVID-19. Again received the risk vs benefit discussion. Patient stated understanding and desire to proceed with the vaccination. He will be monitored for at least 30 minutes in area where staff can directly observe him. Patient received the COVID vaccination at 13:00. At 45 minutes later, staff alerted that he was c/o palpitations. Due to confusion and weakness, we were unable to transport him to an examination room. Oxygen, water, and vitals machine were brought to him. He presented with SOB, confusion, lightheadedness. Exam demonstrated acute distress, speaking in staccato sentences. HR in 80s, with lungs CTAB and no stridor - despite increased RR to 20s. Vitals with HR in 70s, SpO2 remained 97% or greater on RA. BP was initially 140/72. A code blue was called and Drs. presented to the area. Patient c/o itchy throat and still p/w confusion/combativeness, loss of orientation, and SOB. No visible swelling noticed. At around 13:58, patient syncopized. HR and SpO2 remained 70-80s and >98% on room air respectively. Pulse remained palpable. At that time, an epipen was administered. Patient woke up. During the entire episode, he was able to recognize a staff member with whom he was previously familiar. EMS arrived, vitals remained stable. EMS transported patient to the ER for further monitoring and f/u. Concern for immediate allergic reaction 2/2 vaccination. After event, patient in need of referral to allergy provider for evaluation prior to consideration of 2nd dosage.

Death Narrative: Patient received Covid vaccine on 2/2/21, person reports his legs were more rigid with some sweating the day of the vaccination with leg rigidity that was slowly improving. No other adverse effects reported for following 7 days. Person states he had vomiting episode earlier this week, person states he had no other symptoms before or after the vomiting episodes. On morning of 2/12/21, person reports patient got up ready for breakfast with no issues. She says he asked for chorizo and oatmeal but she laughed and said don't you mean chorizo and eggs. He said yes. They got him into W/C and he was rolling himself into dining room got stuck in hallway. She says he took several breaths then 3 very deep breaths and passed away. She called 911 they took his VS but he has passed. She told them to leave him along no resuscitation.

COVID 19 symptoms and a positive test was confirmed on 1/6, employee noted previous exposure to positive family members Narrative: Employee noted exposure to COVID prior to presenting for 1st dose of vaccine on 1/5/21. On 1/6/21 employee reported the onset of symptoms and was tested and was confirmed COVID positive that day. Positive result was reported to employee health on 1/8/21. Employee Health continued to track employees progress and was informed of the need for hospitalization on 1/14/21. Course of hospitalization noted the need for intubation and significant issue with comorbid condition (rheumatoid arthritis). Employee died on 2/9/2021. Unable to confirm a direct connection to Vaccine vs. COVID infection, but felt it should be reported.

Guillain-Barre Syndrome Narrative:  71 year old male with PMH diabetes mellitus type 2 complicated by peripheral neuropathy and cervical and lumbar stenosis, who presented for AIDP/Guillain barre. Patient was in his usual state of health prior to admission. He had an influenza vaccination late October 2020. About three days later he developed numbness and weakness of the bilateral feet and legs. November 3rd he noticed that this began worsening and raising up more proximally up his legs. he also had bilateral hand weakness and numbness which was worsening as well. He presented to a community hospital 11/5 2020 when he also developed bilateral hand numbness and weakness that has been worsening. He was admitted for AIDP . On 11/8/2020 patient required intubation for acute hypoxic respiratory failure due to aspiration and inability to protect airway. He had piperacillin/tazobactam for aspiration pneumonia completed on 11/25/2020, and then was transitioned to amoxicillin/clav. Hospital course was complicated by AKI secondary to contrast induced nephropathy, which peaked to 4.1 before decreasing back to baseline. He received a total of 5 days of IVIG and also suffered from critical illness myopathy. Also has been treated for dysphagia and was on a honey thick liquids and pureed diet. T2DM managed with Detemir 15 units SC BID. Seen by psychiatry on 11/19/2020 for suicidal ideation and cleared at that time (he was started on sertraline 50 mg PO daily). During his acute inpatient rehabilitation stay he initially suffered from delirium with 1 fall while on the unit. He improved drastically after adjustments to his gabapentin. There was suspicion that withdrawal was contributing to his delirium. QTC noted to be prolonged therefore his quetiapine was stopped. Transitioned back to oral antihyperglycemics early in his stay. Initially he was unable to stand secondary to his AIDP and critical illness myopathy. This has improved with therapy. Patient was also initially constipated, but then began having multiple loose stools after being started on an aggressive bowel regimen. He was tested for C diff, which returned negative. Bowel regimen has been titrated down to senna PO QHS. He initially suffered from areflexic bladder with elevated PVRS and no sensation to void. He was trained on intermittent catheterization and sterile cath technique. He eventually developed sensation of needing to void and began having continent voids. Patient had complaints of frequent urination from 4-8 pm. PVR bladder scan followed by a straight cath PVR were obtained, and returned low. It was hypothesized that due to fluid mobilization at the end of the day when patient elevates his BLE triggered his need for frequent urination. He was supplied with a urinal to use in the evenings to minimize the risk of falling. It was discussed that patient may benefit from a urodynamic study in 6 months from discharge. On 12/17/2020 he had acute onset of chills, feeling of recurrent weakness, and malaise. URine found to have bacteria. This was the second UTI he has had since onset of AIDP. CT ordered for R/O Bladder stone, which returned without kidney stones nor bladder stones. However an incidental hyperechoic mass on the kidney was seen bilaterally, with recommendations for MRI renal protocol. Initially patient was placed on trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole, but due to urine culture resulting with E. coli, he was transitioned to cephalexin (finished a 14 day course) and started on methanamine for prophylaxis. Patient was interested in work up of his BUE tremors while he continued to progress in therapy. He was evaluated by neurologist. Labwork work up was unremarkable and symptoms deemed likely secondary to benign familial tremors. Since patient's quality of life was unaffected and he did not have social embarrassment from his tremors, he declined pursuing medication treatment. Plans are for him to follow up with provider in 6 months from discharge. Patient continued to do well throughout his stay. After being seen and examined by attending physician on 1/22/2021, he was deemed stable for discharge home.

I was already weary, and dealing with major stress for weeks before the vaccine. And I had been taking max doses of OTC painkillers for an extracted tooth for over two weeks before the shot. The tooth extraction had problems but because of Covid risk my dentist told me to "tough it out." I took 800mg of ibuprofen and 1000 of Tylenol every six hours for over two weeks.

I was having chest congestion, and shallow breathing, plus heart palpitations, plus constant headaches, and I do not normally get headaches. I thought it was allergies and anxiety, but I finally called my doctor on Feb 4th. He ordered blood tests and found my hormones were "all over the place." This is probably something different altogether. He's doing more blood tests.

On December 17, 2020, my husband, received his first BioNTech BNT162b2 COVID-19 vaccination. On Thursday January 7, 2021, he received this second COVID-19 vaccination. The following three days after his second vaccination, he felt fine. The fourth day, on Sunday January 10, my husband felt extremely fatigued. On Monday the 11th and Tuesday the 12th, he worked a full shift but complained of extreme fatigue and extreme chills to the point that his teeth were chattering while on the phone with me. He decided to work through it. When he got home on Monday night, he started vomiting. On Wednesday January 13, he woke up and had swollen eyes. Once again, he felt extremely fatigued, even after a full nights rest. He had the day off but had an early meeting. After his meeting, he was still tired so he went back to sleep. I left to get lunch, and drop off our kids, and upon my return, I found him on the walk in closet floor, face up, having passed away. He felt as cold as ice. The rapid test done after they called the paramedics resulted in a negative COVID-19 test for him.
LAB_DATA: COVID-19 test after paramedics arrived which came back negative.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client reported feeling nervous prior to receiving vaccine, but informed the vaccinator that she wanted to continue with receiving the vaccination.  About 30 seconds after receiving the vaccine, she reported feeling flushed and dizzy.  Vaccinator assisted her to the side to sit on the ground.  Vitals signs were taken, 15:18: BP 170/110, HR 120, T: 97.3. Client appeared sweaty and skin felt clammy.  Client was provided water and Powerade and encouraged to drink and rest.  Safety and EMS on site were notified and responded.  911 was not activated.  BP was elevated and client reported that she did not know her normal BP, but has heard from her doctor that it is high, but not prescribed daily medication for maintenance.  She reported taking metoprolol as needed.  Vital signs: 15:22: BP 170/110, HR 100; 15:27: BP 164/110; 15:30 (standing): BP 160/114, HR 130; 15:53: BP 140/108, HR 100.  Client continued to rest and was offered additional water, Powerade, and snacks which were declined.  She reported feeling better, vital signs were stable/consistent and she was no longer sweaty and clammy.  She declined an escort back to her car and was released from the vaccination area at 16:10.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 46-year-old female who has known history of previous reactions to immunizations with anaphylaxis as well as seizures who presented to the emergency department with some symptoms after receiving Covid vaccination.  She reported onset of some mild headache and dizziness as well as ringing in her ears.  She states that these are symptoms sometimes that precede a seizure episode.  She has managed on Keppra 750 mg twice daily and has been on this regimen for some time.  Here in the emergency department she had no significant concerning findings on exam.  Vital signs were fairly unremarkable, there was no rash, there is no stridor or throat swelling, lungs were clear.  There is no seizure activity or any other neurological findings.  I spoke at length with the patient and her significant other regarding this symptomatology but I do not see any reason at this time that she would need to be admitted to this hospital.  She could still potentially develop a seizure-like episode although I do not anticipate this to be the case.  There is definitely nothing at this time that would point towards anaphylaxis.  There was a Keppra level that was drawn and is pending at this time.  I have sent a letter to neurology to let them know that it is still pending at this time.

I received Latera absorbable nasal implants (manufacturer Striker) due to collapsed sinus (intraoperatively).  Within a day or two post op, I started having red lines above the implants which swelled.  At first the doc thought it was an infection and I was given Clindamycin and attempted to culture site (only clear fluid with no notable growth).   I have no history of allergies of any kind. There was no improvement. Then I was put on a course of Methylprednisolone and antihistamines (Cetirizine at night and Fexofenadine during the day) to try to slow the response.  Above the implants is less swollen but still red.  The doc said there is a chance this could be related to the Covid-19 vaccine given the other concerns with facial fillers.  There is a concern that if we don't get the response under control I will have a steroid injection in my nose.  And if that doesn't work, I could have scaring in those locations.  The implant does not absorb for 18 months.
LAB_DATA: Attempt to drain the swollen area and two culture swaps on 02/08/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Adverse event: I had anaphylaxis on 2/12/21 that required transport via ambulance to the nearest emergency room for life saving treatment.  Background information. I took a 7 day course of celebrex (200mg orally once daily) on 1/25/21, prescribed by my primary physician for a flare up of low back pain.  A 14 day course was prescribed; I stopped taking it after 7 days because my stomach was getting upset and I didn't want to take it close to my 2nd covid moderna booster. I got my 2nd moderna covid vaccine booster on 2/8/21.  For 1-2 days, my left arm (injection site) was sore and I was mildly fatigued.   I took over the counter advil  (200mg twice daily) and tylenol (500mg twice daily); the day I took advil, I was sneezing and developed signs of allergic rhinitis (congestion/runny eyes and nose). I did not have any other immediate adverse reaction and by Thursday, 2/11, the arm soreness and fatigue resolved.   My low back pain began to bother me again, so I took a 200mg oral dose of celebrex at 7:30a on 2/12/21. I went to work (I am a veterinary neurologist. While at work, at 9:30a on 2/12/21, I had a severe anaphylactic reaction and had to be taken via ambulance to Medical Center.  I developed hives/welts/burning/itching all over my body,  within 5 minutes my throat closed up, I couldn't breathe, I became hypotensive/collapsed; in the ambulance, I was given IM epinephrine; then at the ER, I was given IV steroids (solumedrol), benedryl, famotidine, zofran (due to abdominal pain/nausea) and IV fluids. This stabilized my signs within 1 hour and I improved and was going to be discharged at 2pm. However,  the hives returned at that time, so I was given additional IV benedryl, famotidine, fluids and oral prednisone and kept in the hospital overnight for monitoring; I was discharged to go home on 2/13/21 on a 4 day course of oral famotidine, benedryl and prednisone; I remained itchy and continued sneezing at home on 2/13/21. Today, 2/14/21, all signs of this reaction have resolved.    The ER doctors and myself believe the 2nd moderna covid booster on 2/8/21 stimulated my innate immune system, leading to this anaphylactic reaction to celebrex (a medication I had taken 2 weeks prior with no problem).   The doctors feel the celebrex is what set off the anaphylactic shock, but that my immune system was primed to do so after the vaccine.  In hindsight, I realized that I was having allergic rhinitis symptoms after taking oral advil on 2/9 the day after my booster (which has never happened to me before either). I am a person with no pre-existing allergies of any kind. There was nothing different at all in my routine including food or potential environmental exposures) on 2/12, the day of my anaphylactic reaction, other than my taking a 200mg dose of oral celebrex.  I am not allowed to take NSAIDs until I see an allergist for testing now.   I am reporting this adverse event as I believe the moderna booster caused an anaphylaxis to the celebrex medication.
LAB_DATA: CBC/Chemistry panel at ER on 2/12/21 - I was told there were no significant abnormalities
OTHER_MEDS: No medications were being taken at the time/day of vaccination on 2/8/21 (the day I received my 2nd moderna covid vaccine)
CUR_ILL: Chronic low back and neck pain. no other illnesses
HISTORY: Chronic low back and neck pain
ALLERGIES: No pre-existing known allergies of any kind (prior to the  reaction I am reporting on 2/12)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have HSV-2.  Outbreaks are rare.  When they occur they happen on my left buttock and in my coccyx area.  After my 2nd Moderna shot, I experienced known symptoms (slight fever, chills, body aches, headaches)  for about 12 hours beginning at about midnight on 2/10/2021.  These symptoms subsided at about 12P on 2/11.  At around 11P on 2/12, while sleeping, I felt a strange abrasion near the right corner of my mouth.  I awoke to what appeared to be a herpes sore in the corner of my mouth.  Over the next couple of hours this sore  balloned into what I would describe as a severe herpes outbreak in an area where I have never had one before.  It is a cluster of several discrete blisters at the corner of my mouth.  I am assuming since I have HSV 2 that that is what these blisters are and for some reason the vaccine triggered this response.  I wanted to report  it because a) it is in a place where I have never had an outbreak and b) I thought there might be a chance that it's not HSV 2 and that the vaccine may cause this reaction in some people.  I am treating the outbreak with famciclovir.   I am reporting this on 12/14 and the blisters are still active and underlying skin area is red/ angry. Thank you.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: a 62 y/o M  who presents with concerns for an allergic reaction to the second dose of the Covid vaccine.  According to him he got the vaccine around 8:45 AM.  He has a history of anaphylactic type reactions with a swelling and urticaria in the past but has not had any symptoms in the last 5 years.  He felt sudden onset pit in his stomach, tingling and warm sensations over his face and some chest tightness.  He denies all the symptoms currently.  He did get medications prior to arrival but states his symptoms were already getting better before he been given anything.  He was given epinephrine as well as Benadryl beforehand.  He denies any symptoms currently.  Denies headache, change in vision, difficulty swallowing, lightheadedness or vertigo, chest pain, sore throat, wheezing, cough, nausea or vomiting, rash, falls or injuries.  Denies any recent foreign travel or sick contacts.  He did work a full shift yesterday and was coming off a 24-hour shift prior to getting his vaccination. He denies any significant reactions to the first vaccine.   Medical Decision Making  On initial presentation is an overall well-appearing 62-year-old male who has normal vital signs without fever or tachycardia.  He is presenting with concern for allergic reaction of the field to a recent vaccination.  The vaccine was given roughly 1 hour prior to arrival. He was given epinephrine intramuscularly as well as IV Benadryl.  He states he is currently feeling mildly tired from the Benadryl. He denies any other recurrent symptomatology and feels better.  Examination is not concerning for anaphylaxis at this time, no evidence of airway involvement or multisystem involvement.  No evidence of local allergic reaction.  Low clinical concern for occult infection, metabolic abnormality, ACS or arrhythmia for a cause of his symptoms.  He is overall very well-appearing.  Labs have been obtained as part of screening for reactions to the vaccination per CDC recommendations including a tryptase and C4 complement.  They were drawn over an hour after the vaccine was administered. ECG was within normal limits.  After observation patient remained asymptomatic.  Did offer steroids, however he wanted to hold off on them as he just got his vaccination which seems appropriate at this time.  He was sent home with a new EpiPen.  We also gave him follow-up in the allergy clinic.  He has any worsening symptoms we do recommend he use the EpiPen as well as call 911.  He is understanding.  At this point he stable for outpatient management.  I did tell him he should expect to feel aches and potentially have inflammatory response to the vaccine, he is understanding of this.  Pt was discharged home/self-care. Pt provided strict return precautions, including but not limited to, any worsening symptoms or any new concerning symptoms. Otherwise, Pt instructed to see PCP on an as needed basis.
LAB_DATA: Complement C4 = 24 mg/dL (normal range 13-50) Tryptase PENDING
